      "file_name": "04_grammar_focus.md",
      "content": "This week, we explore the accusative case for first declension nouns. The accusative case is used to indicate the direct object of a verb, answering the question 'whom?' or 'what?'. For first declension nouns, the accusative singular ends in '-am' and the accusative plural ends in '-as'.\n\nBuilding on our knowledge of nominative forms, we now see how nouns change when they are the object of an action. For example, 'puella' (girl) becomes 'puellam' when she is the one being seen or called.\n\nChant:\n```\nSingular: -am\nPlural: -as\n```\n\nThis chant helps us remember the endings that signal the accusative case, reinforcing our understanding of noun roles in sentences."
